# Tauri v2 Global Shortcut Implementation Code Examples

## Rust Handler Setup

The core Rust implementation registers global shortcuts and handles window visibility toggling:

```rust
fn _register_shortcut_upon_start(app: &App, shortcut: Shortcut) {
    let window = app.get_webview_window("main").unwrap();
    app.handle()
        .plugin(
            tauri_plugin_global_shortcut::Builder::new()
                .with_handler(move |_app, scut, event| {
                    if scut == &shortcut {
                        if let ShortcutState::Pressed = event.state() {
                            if window.is_visible().unwrap() {
                                window.hide().unwrap();
                            } else {
                                window.show().unwrap();
                                window.set_focus().unwrap();
                            }
                        }
                    }
                })
                .build(),
        )
        .unwrap();
    app.global_shortcut().register(shortcut).unwrap();
}
```

## JavaScript Registration

Frontend registration uses the `@tauri-apps/plugin-global-shortcut` package:

```javascript
import { register } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-global-shortcut';

await register('CommandOrControl+Shift+C', () => {
  console.log('Shortcut triggered');
});
```

## Window Toggle Logic

The implementation uses "a toggle window visibility" approach—pressing the shortcut hides a visible window or shows and focuses a hidden one. The Rust handler checks visibility state and calls either `hide()` or `show()` with `set_focus()` accordingly.

## Command Invocation

Frontend calls Rust command to change shortcuts:

```rust
#[tauri::command]
pub fn change_shortcut<R: Runtime>(
    app: AppHandle<R>,
    _window: tauri::Window<R>,
    key: String,
) -> Result<(), String> {
    let shortcut = key.parse::<Shortcut>()?;
    let store = app.get_store("coco_tauri_store")?;
    store.set("coco_global_shortcut", JsonValue::String(key));
    _register_shortcut(&app, shortcut);
    Ok(())
}
```

